pull_request.title: fix: remove conflicting /static/css route that blocked user CSS files
pull_request.body:
## Summary
- Fixes static file serving issue where user CSS files in `/static/css/` were returning 404
- Removes conflicting `/static/css/{filename}` route that was intercepting requests
- Adds `static_path` parameter to `StarHTML` constructor for better usability

## Problem
StarHTML had a built-in route `/static/css/{filename}` that intercepted all requests to `/static/css/*` before the general static file serving route could handle them. This route was looking for CSS files in StarHTML's package directory (which doesn't exist), causing user files to return 404.

## Solution  
Removed the conflicting route. Now user files in `/static/css/` are correctly served by the general static file route.

commits.message: fix: fixed mobile nav and header css
Outlier detection and removal using IQR

[ottf_console] clear out SPI console buffer on init

When the GPIO TX indicator pin is used in conjunction with the SPI
console, the console buffer was not being cleared out when the SPI
console was initialized by the OTTF. This updates the OTTF console to
clear out the SPI device flash buffer during initialization.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[ottf_console] buffer SPI console data in SW

When using the spi_device transport for the OTTF console, a header is
attached to every data payload before writing the data payload to the
spi_device flash buffer (to be later read out by the host). This creates
a large overhead (12-bytes) when the data payload is small (e.g., only a
single character).

Moreover, the way the UJSON message transmit macros are implemented,
results in writing several small strings, or even single characters, to
the printf (console) sink function. This created an unncessarily large
number of SPI console frames when sending the `perso_blob_t` UJSON
struct to the host.

This commit adds a SW buffering mechanism to the OTTF SPI console to
collect all small strings / single character writes into a single large
SPI console transaction. This greatly improves the efficiency in sending
large UJSON structs over the SPI OTTF console.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[ottf_console] make putbuf buffering configurable

The `ottf_console_putbuf()` function had previously buffered data if the
backend console peripheral was SPI (instead of UART). Rather than make
this feature device based, this makes the buffering feature toggle-able
by an kOttfTestConfig parameter. This satisfies review feedback here:
https://github.com/lowRISC/opentitan/pull/27063#issuecomment-2839378315

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[ottf,console] Factor spi_device buffer writing code

Signed-off-by: Amaury Pouly <amaury.pouly@lowrisc.org>

[topgen] Pass through ipgen params to the ipgen config

This allows the user to arbitrarily set ipgen params on ipgen
IPs. These parameters are passed through to the ipgen renderings
This allows integrators to easily define custom ipgen parameters
and get them used without changes in topgen.

Signed-off-by: Robert Schilling <rschilling@rivosinc.com>

[hw,dma,doc] Update the spec for sign-off

Signed-off-by: Robert Schilling <rschilling@rivosinc.com>

[sw/crypto] Add second RSA padding check as a FI countermeasure

Signed-off-by: Hakim Filali <hfilali@lowrisc.org>

[crypto,sw] Add is on curve checks to scalar_mult_int

This commit adds is on curve checks each time scalar_mult_int
is executed. This serves as an FI countermeasure. In case a fault
is injected to get an invalid point such that the secret can be
leaked this will be caught by the is on curve check.

Signed-off-by: Hakim Filali <hfilali@lowrisc.org>

[cryptolib,sw] Add instruction count checks to ECC functions

This commit adds instruction count checks to ECC functions that
run in constant time. This helps protect against fault injection.

Signed-off-by: Hakim Filali <hfilali@lowrisc.org>

[crypto,sw] Add is on curve check to base point mult

This commit adds a is on curve check to the base point
multiplication after the multiplication is done. This
validates that the product is still on the curve and
acts as a fault injection countermeasure.

Signed-off-by: Hakim Filali <hfilali@lowrisc.org>

[ipgen] Fix loading of ipconfig from a file

When `dtgen` support was added to the ipconfig, only the constructor
was updated but not the code loading from a file. Since topgen directly
calls the constructor, this was not caught in CI but it throws an error
if running ipgen directly, e.g.
  util/ipgen.py generate
    -C hw/ip_templates/ac_range_check
    -o hw/top_darjeeling/ip_autogen/ac_range_check
    -c hw/top_darjeeling/ip_autogen/ac_range_check/data/top_darjeeling_ac_range_check.ipconfig.hjson
    -f

Signed-off-by: Amaury Pouly <amaury.pouly@lowrisc.org>

[crypto] Fix shift in p256_random_scalar share generation

This commit fixes a bug where the most significant 64 bits were
constantly set to 0 instead to the actual seed.

Thanks Yi-Hsuan Deng for spotting this!

Signed-off-by: Pascal Nasahl <nasahlpa@lowrisc.org>

[crypto] Fix comment in p384_random_scalar share generation

The comment describes that the code selects bits [192:0] for
the shares stored in w9 and w7. However, the code actually
selects bits [255:64].

Signed-off-by: Pascal Nasahl <nasahlpa@lowrisc.org>

[rom_ext] build multiple ROM_EXTs with different cert formats

This builds two different base ROM_EXTs to support different DICE
certificate formats, namely: X.509 and CWT formats. This partially
addresses #24281.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[dice,rom_ext] support CWT CDI_* cert updates

This complete the implementation of the `dice_cert_check_valid()`
function in the `dice_cwt` library to enable regenerating DICE CWT CDI_*
certs in the ROM_EXT if firmware is ever updated. This fixes #24281.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[manuf] only verify X.509 DICE chain with openssl

DICE certs can be generated in X.509 or CWT format during perso. OpenSSL
can only verify X.509 cert chains. This updates the perso flow to only
check if the DICE cert chain verifies successfully if the certs are
X.509 format until a new tool (`hwtrust`) can be used to validate the
CWT chain.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>

[sw] Separate dice abstract interface library

This commit separates the interface out for the dice users to depend on. The
actual implementation will be chosen by the rom_ext linking dependencies.

Change-Id: Ibc218fa5b6ac0fc5314c1f5816995cb9ed957bb6
Signed-off-by: Yi-Hsuan Deng <yhdeng@google.com>

[sw,imm_rom_ext] Parameterize binary bazel target by slot

Parameterize binary bazel target by slot

This change uses list comprehension to generate the immutable rom_ext targets,
rather than repeating the rules for each individual slot.

Change-Id: Ifa1b36e293af0489909baf5a30366380643332ed
Signed-off-by: Yi-Hsuan Deng <yhdeng@google.com>

[sw,imm_rom_ext] Match dice variations

The immutable rom_ext was previously always linked to the x509 dice variant.
This commit creates the cwt dice variant, and links it to the
corresponding mutable rom_ext target.

Change-Id: If27e8a080daba9f3ebf6c52f1783658ad5966960
Signed-off-by: Yi-Hsuan Deng <yhdeng@google.com>

[rom_ext] fix CDI_* update bug

If non-CWT CDI certs are found in flash info page 19, we should treat
this case as if the cert page is empty, and regenerate the certs. This
enables running an X.509 ROM_EXT first and changing to a CWT ROM_EXT
later. Since UDS cert is never generated outside perso (and is on a
separate flash page), the UDS cert format is defined at provisioning
time.

Signed-off-by: Tim Trippel <ttrippel@google.com>
